{
  "doc_id": "46411",
  "text": "Few MR imaging morphometry studies exist in pediatric BPD. Currently, only 4 published studies have examined volumetric changes in cortical or subcortical structures in adolescents with BPD. Two have found decreased amygdalar volume in adolescents with BPD compared with controls, with one of these also finding a reduction in hippocampal volume. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] A third study found that adolescents with BPD had decreased left superior temporal gyrus volume. [CITATION_3] Recently, a fourth study used VBM to evaluate 12 ROIs in 10 adolescents with BPD and found that, compared with controls, the patients had increased gray matter volume bilaterally in the basal ganglia and thalamus, as well as larger left temporal lobes. [CITATION_4] In addition, investigators have found evidence of increased white matter hyperintensities in children with BPD, but this finding may lack specificity since similar increases have been reported in children with other psychiatric disorders. [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] Clearly, more neuroimaging studies are needed in children with BPD to enhance our understanding of the developmental psychobiology of the illness.",
